text:
She was the ultimate bad girl of the 1990s

And after scrapping in a carpark with co-star Jennie Garth and crashing her friend Ian Ziering's expensive sport's car, Shannen Doherty finally goes too far when she messes with the boss's daughter on The Unauthorized Beverly Hills 90210 Story.

The dramatized Lifetime recreation of the hit show’s backstory showed executive producer Aaron spelling repeatedly defending the show's breakout star despite her bad behavior - including fights, arrests, and chronic lateness.

Scroll down for video

Taking it too far: Shannen Doherty seals her fate by threating Tori Spelling on Lifetime's Unauthorized Beverly Hills 90210 Story

But it the final straw came when the rock-headed actress picked on the wrong person - Spelling’s own daughter Tori, played by Donna Martin in the drama.

The Unauthorized Story suggested that the sexpot starlet walked in on the rest of the cast as they all voted to try to get her booted from their show - with only Tori standing by her, telling the others: ‘I like Shannen. She’s my friend.’

But after Tori walked away in disgust at her co-star's latest lame excuses for being so late, Shannen - played in the drama by Samantha Munro - made her biggest mistake by picking on the daughter of the show’s boss.

‘You better watch you’re back,’ Shannen is seen warning Tori, played in the Lifetime recreation by Abby Ross.

Union busting: Shannen walks in on her castmates plotting against her after turning up late yet again

Spelling mistake: She blunders by clashing with her only friend left on the show

I'm telling my daddy on you: And it is not long before Aaron decides to pull the trigger on the bad girl

Party on dude: She paraphrases era stalwarts Bill and Ted by saying she cannot wait to party hard

Gabrielle Carteris, played Michele Goyns, predicted that it would be a fatal move by her co-star.

‘What do you think the employee handbook says about threatening your boss’s daughter?’ she asked Jason Priestley, played by Max Lloyd-Jones.

The Lifetime drama suggested it was the final straw, with the next scene cutting to a news announcement about Shannen’s departure, and a smiling Aaron telling colleagues that they were nicer to her than they could have been.

But the drama suggests it was a complete u-turn from his attitude from before Shannen offended his daughter, showing him stand up for her despite a barrage of complaints about her behavior, being told the entire cast and crew ‘loathe her’.

Garth brooks a grudge: Jennie challenges her foe to a punch up after she pinches her during a scene

The fighting Irish: And Shannen is only too happy to take her outside for some fisticuffs

Ready to explode: Jennie is fuming as they get ready to tussle in the parking lot

How does this grab you: But Shannen is just as angry and gives her foe some whiplash

‘I understand, and I’ve heard everyone,’ Aaron, played by Dan Castellaneta, had insisted. ‘But as far as I’m concerned Shannen stays.’

But the drama suggested Tori was a key figure not just in the end of Shannen’s run on the show - but even for the show ever getting going in the first place.

As her father initially showed no interest in a pitch for the show, the Unauthorized Story suggests some key chats with Tori turned him around.

‘Every show you make is for adults,’ she complained to him in an early scene.

Coming to 9021 blows: The dynamic duo engage in a shoving match in glamorous Van Nuys

No need to be so pushy: They end up shoving each other back and forward as things heat up

Watch my bodywork: Jason Priestley is none to pleased when Garth ends up sprawled on his bonnet

‘There’s a lot of cool young actors around who never get the chance to do anything good,’ she complained, insisting: ‘I’m really good.’

She then warned him: ‘Maybe the reason you don’t have any shows on right now is because the audience is getting younger and cooler.’

The drama suggested she also made a key decision when her dad could not find suitable stars to play the two main characters, brother and sister Brenda and Brandon Walsh, with Tori suggesting both Shannen and Jason Priestley.

Pep talk gone bad: Ian Ziering takes her out for a spin in his sports car to pass on some advice but ends up being talked into letting her drive it

He will want to throttle her in a minute: She slams on the gas and soon loses control of the powerful motor

Fender's pancake: She smashes his precious vehicle into a construction site

Fall guy: And he tries to avoid getting his friend in trouble by saying he was the one behind the wheel

The drama also insisted that Tori genuinely impressed everyone with her acting during her audition - even thought they knew who she really was despite using the name Tori Mitchell.

‘Who would have known?’ one of the casting director asked in supposed amazement at her skills that his colleague called ‘great’.

Luke Perry - played by Jesy McKinney - has the most interesting hiring story, as he is seen digging roads in a construction job before going for the audition.

After initially failing to land the first part he auditioned for, he was called back to play bad boy Dylan McKay when the pilot proved it needed an edgy character - with Luke supposedly having to borrow a shirt for the audition and then grumpily smoking throughout.

No more Love Boat daddy: Aaron is portrayed as being stuck in the times in the film

Interesting Tori: In fact his daughter pushes him to make the show and even makes casting suggestions

Priestley, meanwhile, is seen with a roommate at their scruffy home when a script is delivered - but it actually being the Thelma & Louise script for their other roommate, Brad Pitt.

‘Pitt’s not home. Come to think of it, he’s hardly ever home these days,’ the roommate told the delivery guy, before telling Priestley he should also audition for the movie role. ‘You’re definitely as pretty as Pitt,’ he teased him.

When the show starts - with the actors taking very humble dressing rooms in a studio covered in boxes and garbage - they seem convinced the show will not take off, but soon appear to form fast friendships.

Priestley and Doherty, in fact, are shown appearing a little too friendly in their audition - repeatedly being told not to be so flirty and intimate as they will be playing brother and sister.

Paving the way to success: Wannabe Luke Perry's true talent is revealed when he is shown laying a road

Looking to score a hit: Garth crooks her neck up when she hears about the show in development

Soaring success: After a faltering start the show is a massive hit thanks to strong summer run

Luke Perry is then seen getting a little too frisky with Doherty, grabbing her breast during a scene - and insisting: ‘That’s where the hands go, I have no control over them.’

It is an intimacy that supposedly soon takes hold amongst the cast off-screen, too, with one crew member insisting: ‘Everyone is making out with everyone.’

Sex also causes problems onscreen when an episode showing Shannen’s character losing her video loses advertisers.

That put a smile on her face: The show lovingly recreated the then controversial moment Shannen's character Brenda Walsh boasted about losing her virginity

Taking one for the team: The show's creator had to beg Perry and Doherty to film a scene where they regret their actions

Trappings of success: Perry and Priestley are soon munching burgers at high-end restaurants

You do Ron? President Reagan is even seen interrupting their meal to tell them he is a big fan of the show

Modern day Beatles: The dynamic duo are mobbed by excited young women wherever they go

‘This is important - this is about delivering a real message,’ show creator Darren Star complained when told the have to change the situation and see Shannen upset about having sex.

‘We live in a world where a girl doesn’t have to be totally shamed for losing her virginity. We probably showed the most sophisticated depiction of teen sex in the history of television,’ he insisted, but ultimately losing his battle.

The drama shows how 90210 became so popular Aaron told the actors they were ‘about to become The Beatles’.

And Priestley and Perry are then seen at lunch getting greeted by President Ronald Reagan, who told them: ‘I know you’re show is quite popular, Nancy and I have actually watched it.’

Joking that they are ‘probably not your demographic’, the President is supposed to have then told them he could ‘use you on Capital Hill’ if they remain so popular.

Nightclub brawl: Shannen jumps in for wimp Brian Austin Green after he is threatened at a nightspot

Fighting Irish part two: And Doherty proves quite able to handle herself against the bigger man

While the male stars are all seen being best buddies off-screen, too, Shannen’s constant lateness starts annoying everyone - and a clear feud is shown with Jennie Garth, played by Abbie Cobb.

It gets so bad they are seen storming off set to have a fight - with Perry and Priestley having to pull them apart.

Shannen is shown supposedly apologizing to Garth when they are left alone during a night out at The Roxbury nightclub - before she then gets arrested for attacking a fellow clubber who had picked on Brian Austin Green, played by Ross Linton.

The officer giving her her ticket for ‘misdemeanor battery’ sums up the general public’s opinion of Doherty at this time, telling her: ‘Do I know who you are? Yes. You are a big pain in the ass. Everybody thinks that.’

Do you know who I am: She tries to pull her favourite trick when a police offer cites her for battery

Even he watches the show: But he makes clear he dislikes her character on the show as he gives her the ticket

Big news: Once again Shannen's antics are drawing the attention of the showbusiness media

Perhaps the silliest line of the drama comes as Ian Ziering, played by David Lennon, takes Shannen for a drive to try to talk some sense in her, a scene ending with her then crashing his sports car.

‘You’re acting crazy - you’re out of control,’ he told her. ‘You’re like a shark, you’re like a tornado - you’re like a mixture between a shark and a tornado,’ he said, the writers’ clear reference to Ziering’s current fame from Sharknado.

‘That’s the dumbest thing I’ve ever heard,’ Shannen’s character shoots back.

Austin Green gets the harshest portrayal, shown throughout as a nerd who everyone teases for his bad dancing and love of hip hop.

But he ended on a high as new cast member Tiffani-Amber Thiessen, played by Alyssa Lynch, walks in, and he immediately walks up to kiss and hug her and introduce her as ‘my girl’ to his cast mates’ clear shock.

Having the last laugh: The show poked fun at the fact she later had starred in Aaron's hit show Charmed in which she played a witch

9021 doh: In the movie it is suggested Doherty had clashed with Garth and Spelling over wearing a red dress for a cast still
